'''Adrian Lamo''' (born February 20, 1981{{citation needed|date=June 2013}}) is an [[United States|American]] [[threat analyst]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.facebook.com/felon |title=Adrian Lamo on Facebook |author= Adrin Lamo |date=17 November 2013 |accessdate=17 November 2013}}</ref> and former [[Hacker (computer security)|hacker]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://articles.washingtonpost.com/2013-06-04/world/39729591_1_hacker-adrian-lamo-ashden-fein-manning-s |title=Hacker Adrian Lamo testifies at WikiLeaks suspect Bradley Manning’s court-martial |publisher=[[Washington Post]] |date=04 June 2013 |accessdate=07 September 2013}}</ref>

Lamo first gained media attention for breaking into several high-profile computer networks, including those of ''[[The New York Times]]'', [[Yahoo!]], and [[Microsoft]], culminating in his 2003 arrest.<ref name=kahn>{{cite web|url=http://www.wired.com/wired/archive/12.04/hacker_pr.html |title=Wired 12.04: The Homeless Hacker v. The New York Times |publisher=Wired.com |date= |accessdate=2013-08-25}}</ref>  In 2010, Lamo reported U.S. soldier Pfc. Bradley Manning (later known as [[Chelsea Manning]]) to federal authorities, claiming that Manning had [[internet leak|leaked]] hundreds of thousands of sensitive U.S. government documents to [[WikiLeaks]]. Manning was arrested and incarcerated in the U.S. military justice system and later sentenced to 35 years in confinement.<ref>
{{cite news
  | last = Poulsen
  | first = Kevin
