</ref>

==Personal life==
Lamo was born in [[Boston, Massachusetts]] to Mario Lamo and Mary Atwood around 1981.<ref name="mpalm03">
{{cite web
  | last = Palmquist
  | first = Matt
  | title = A Duty to Hack
  | publisher = [[SF Weekly]]
  | date = April 16, 2003
  | url = http://www.sfweekly.com/2003-04-16/news/a-duty-to-hack/full/
  | accessdate = June 8, 2013}}
</ref> According to Jennifer Kahn of ''[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]'', Lamo was known as the "Homeless Hacker" for his supposedly transient lifestyle. Lamo has claimed that he has spent much of his travels [[CouchSurfing|couch-surfing]], squatting in abandoned buildings and traveling to [[Internet cafe]]s, libraries and universities to investigate networks, and sometimes exploiting security holes.<ref name=kahn /> Despite performing authorized and unauthorized [[vulnerability assessment]]s for several large, high-profile entities, Lamo has claimed he refused to accept payment for his services.<ref name=hacks>{{cite web
  | last = Shachtman
  | first = Noah
  | title = He Hacks By Day, Squats By Night
  | work = [[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]
  | date = March 6, 2002
  | url = http://www.wired.com/culture/lifestyle/news/2002/03/50811?currentPage=all
  | accessdate = March 20, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news
  | last = Fantz
  | first = Ashley
  | title = On WikiLeaks scandal, hacker says he didn't want to be a coward
  | publisher = CNN
  | date = July 29, 2010
  | url = http://www.cnn.com/2010/US/07/29/lamo.profile.wikileaks/index.html
  | accessdate = March 20, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web
  | author = The Week Staff
  | title = Who is hacker hero Adrian Lamo
  | publisher = [[The Week]]
  | date = June 16, 2010
  | url = http://theweek.com/article/index/204061/wikileaks-who-is-hacker-hero-adrian-lamo
  | accessdate = March 20, 2013}}</ref>

In the mid-1990s, Lamo became a volunteer for the gay and lesbian media firm [[PlanetOut.com]].<ref name=hacks/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.wired.com/wired/archive/12.04/hacker_pr.html |title=Wired 12.04: The Homeless Hacker v. The New York Times |publisher=Wired.com |date= |accessdate=2011-12-20}}</ref> In 1998, Lamo was appointed to the Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual, Transgender, Queer and Questioning Youth Task Force by the [[San Francisco Board of Supervisors]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldtribune.com/worldtribune/WTARC/2010/ss_military0732_08_02.asp |title=Report: U.S. Army homosexual tied to WikiLeaks scandal |publisher=Worldtribune.com |date= |accessdate=2013-08-25}}</ref><ref>
{{cite web
  | title = Agenda & Minutes Archive
  | publisher = [[San Francisco Board of Supervisors]]
  | date = August 3, 1998
  | url = http://www.sfbos.org/index.aspx?page=2723
  | accessdate = October 23, 2010
  | quote = Adrian Lamo, Seat No. 10}}
</ref>  

During this period, in 2001, he overdosed on prescription amphetamines.<ref name="mpalm03"/><ref name="jkahn04"/>

In a 2004 interview with ''[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]'', an ex-girlfriend of Lamo's described him as "very controlling," stating, "He carried a [[electroshock weapon|stun gun]], which he used on me." According to the same article, a court issued a restraining order against Lamo.<ref name="jkahn04">
{{cite news
  | last = Kahn
  | first = Jennifer
  | title = The Homeless Hacker v. The New York Times
  | publisher = [[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]
  | year = 2004
  | url = http://www.wired.com/wired/archive/12.04/hacker_pr.html
  | accessdate = July 8, 2010}}
</ref> Lamo disputed the accuracy of the article and wrote, "I have never been subject to a restraining order in my life".<ref>{{cite web
  | last = Lamo
  | first = Adrian
  | title = Citability (is important!)
  | publisher = God, Sex, & the FBI: Adrian Lamo's (alleged) blog
  | date = July 10, 2010
  | url = http://pax.vox.com/library/post/citability-is-important.html
  | accessdate = July 10, 2010}}{{Dead link|date=October 2010}}</ref>

Lamo claimed in a ''Wired'' article that in May 2010, after reporting his backpack stolen, an investigating officer noted unusual behavior and detained him. He was diagnosed with [[Asperger syndrome|Asperger's syndrome]] after having been placed on a 72-hour involuntary psychiatric hold, which was extended to a total of nine days.<ref>
{{cite news
  | last = Poulsen
  | first = Kevin
  | authorlink = Kevin Poulsen
  | title = Ex-Hacker Adrian Lamo Institutionalized for Asperger’s
  | publisher = [[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]
