===Security compromise===
In December 2001, Lamo was praised by [[Worldcom]] for helping to fortify their corporate security.<ref>{{cite web|last=Poulsen|first=Kevin|title=FBI reportedly hunting Adrian Lamo|url=http://www.theregister.co.uk/2003/09/05/fbi_reportedly_hunting_adrian_lamo/|publisher=The Register}}</ref> In February 2002 he broke into the internal computer network of ''The New York Times'', adding his name to the internal database of expert sources, and using the paper's [[LexisNexis]] account to conduct research on high-profile subjects. The ''New York Times'' filed a complaint, and a warrant for Lamo's arrest was issued in August 2003 following a 15-month investigation by federal prosecutors in New York. At 10:15 AM on September 9, after spending a few days in hiding, he surrendered to the [[United States Marshals Service|US Marshals]] in [[Sacramento, California]]. He re-surrendered to the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]] in New York City on September 11, and pled guilty to one felony count of [[computer crime]]s against [[Microsoft]], [[LexisNexis]] and ''[[The New York Times]]'' on January 8, 2004.<ref>{{cite web|first=Noah|last=Shachtman |url=http://www.wired.com/techbiz/it/news/2004/01/61831 |title="Adrian Lamo Cuts Deal With Feds" |publisher=Wired.com |date= |accessdate=2013-08-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Kevin Poulsen |url=http://www.securityfocus.com/news/7771 |title="Lamo Pleads Guilty to Times Hack" |publisher=Securityfocus.com |date=2004-01-08 |accessdate=2013-08-25}}</ref> 

Later in 2004, Lamo was sentenced to six months detention at his parents' home plus two years probation, and was ordered to pay roughly $65,000 in restitution. He was convicted of compromising security at ''[[The New York Times]]'' and [[Microsoft]],<ref>
{{cite web
